<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=53801" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=53801</a></p><p>
<i>Republikein Online,</i> 4 November 2009, <br/>
<a href="http://www.republikein.com.na/se-jou-se/would-the-signing-of-the-interim-epa-remedy-the-woes-of-the-local-beef-industry.96771.php" target="_self">http://www.republikein.com.na/se-jou-se/would-the-signing-of-the-interim...</a></p><p>
ICTSD, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest, </i>Vol. 13, No. 38, 4 November 2009 <br/>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/58560/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/58560/</a></p><p>
<i>Jakarta Post</i>, 11 November 2009 <br/>
<a href="http://www.bilaterals.org/article.php3?id_article=16270" target="_self">http://www.bilaterals.org/article.php3?id_article=16270</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The question arises of how these various new and pending agreements will affect the future value of ACP trade preferences. This is a particularly relevant question in the context of the ongoing EPA negotiations, as some ACP countries are signing interim EPAs (IEPAs) solely to preserve preferential access to the EU market. As one ACP observer has already asked, what is the value of signing IEPAs to preserve preferential access to the EU market if the value of that preferential access is rapidly being eroded? This is a question which ACP governments contemplating signing an IEPA will need to assess in the light of their underlying motivation for signing, the structure of their country’s current exports to the EU and the current trend towards erosion of the value of traditional ACP trade preferences. </p><p>The SPS provisions included in the EU-South Korea agreement could potentially be of interest to ACP exporters such as Namibia, which on the one hand is in dispute with the EU over recognition of disease-free areas and, on the other hand, finds its beef exports to Korea blocked on SPS grounds.</p><p>The interview in the Jakarta Post with the EC lead negotiator raises the further question of why, if the level of development of Myanmar is such that ‘there is no way [the EU] could have a reciprocal FTA with an economy of that order’, the EC should be so vigorously pursuing FTA arrangements with least-developed ACP countries whose economic status is on a par with Myanmar. </p><p>The question arises of how these various new and pending agreements will affect the future value of ACP trade preferences. This is a particularly relevant question in the context of the ongoing EPA negotiations, as some ACP countries are signing interim EPAs (IEPAs) solely to preserve preferential access to the EU market. As one ACP observer has already asked, what is the value of signing IEPAs to preserve preferential access to the EU market if the value of that preferential access is rapidly being eroded? This is a question which ACP governments contemplating signing an IEPA will need to assess in the light of their underlying motivation for signing, the structure of their country’s current exports to the EU and the current trend towards erosion of the value of traditional ACP trade preferences. </p><p>The SPS provisions included in the EU-South Korea agreement could potentially be of interest to ACP exporters such as Namibia, which on the one hand is in dispute with the EU over recognition of disease-free areas and, on the other hand, finds its beef exports to Korea blocked on SPS grounds.</p><p>The interview in the Jakarta Post with the EC lead negotiator raises the further question of why, if the level of development of Myanmar is such that ‘there is no way [the EU] could have a reciprocal FTA with an economy of that order’, the EC should be so vigorously pursuing FTA arrangements with least-developed ACP countries whose economic status is on a par with Myanmar. </p>
		</div>
		

	</article>


</section>							
<section class="content newsletterline">
	<article>

		<div class="left">
													<img src="/extension/agritrade/design/agritrade/images/pubtypes/newsanalysis.gif" alt=""/>
					

		</div>

				<header>






		
																																																				
		
		<div class='contentrealtionlist'>
							
																																																								
								<a href="/en/Publications/(regions)/7769/(search)/simple">All ACP</a>
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																					
																																,

							<a href="/en/Agriculture/(commodities)/7795/(search)/simple">General</a>
							
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																													
																																																						,

							<a href="/en/Agriculture/(topics)/7813/(search)/simple">EPAs</a>
							
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																					
							
		</div>
		
					<h1>Résolution ACP sur les APE</h1>

			<h4>
			
												09 December 2009
										</h4>

				</header>







		
		
					<p>A l’occasion de la 90e session du Conseil des ministres ACP, une résolution a été adoptée sur les APE et d’autres sujets liés au commerce. Parmi les enjeux soulevés, la résolution a exhorté la CE « à doter le processus des APE d’une véritable flexibilité, de façon à ce que les régions ACP puissent proposer des offres d’accès au marché inférieures au seuil de 80% des échanges pour une période de transition supérieure à 15 ans » et appelle « à une amélioration des règles d’origine, notamment dans la perspective de favoriser un cumul total au niveau tous-ACP avec des PED voisins. La résolution convient également « de la nécessité d’aborder la libéralisation des produits de base avec prudence, étant donné que la CE continue de recourir aux subventions ». La résolution a également réitéré sa préoccupation sur le fait que les ressources financières disponibles ne seront pas suffisantes pour faire face aux coûts d’ajustement et a appelé à l’adoption de dispositions contraignantes relatives à la coopération au développement au titre des APE.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Secrétariat ACP, Résolution des ministres ACP, ACP/25/014/09, 19 novembre 2009<br/>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id=5186&amp;doc_language=Both" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Les analyses d’autres ALE suggèrent que la couverture des produits peut souvent être nettement inférieure à 80% de l’ensemble des échanges et, en effet, l’ouverture des marchés pour les produits européens peut être d’à peine 54,09% (conformément à l’ALE UE-Mexique : cf. article suivant sur l’étude AFD-GRET). Il semblerait par conséquent qu’il y ait un précédent pour l’adoption de la proposition ACP en vue d’intégrer dans les négociations APE une « véritable flexibilité ». </p>
		</div>
		

	</article>


</section>							
<section class="content newsletterline">
	<article>

		<div class="left">
													<img src="/extension/agritrade/design/agritrade/images/pubtypes/newsanalysis.gif" alt=""/>
					

		</div>

				<header>






		
																																																											
		
		<div class='contentrealtionlist'>
							
																																																								
								<a href="/en/Publications/(regions)/7769/(search)/simple">All ACP</a>
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																														
																																,

							<a href="/en/Agriculture/(commodities)/7795/(search)/simple">General</a>
							
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																													
																																																						,

							<a href="/en/Agriculture/(topics)/7813/(search)/simple">EPAs</a>
							
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																					
							
		</div>
		
					<h1>AFD-GRET study shows potential flexibility for current EPA negotiations</h1>

			<h4>
			
												09 December 2009
										</h4>

				</header>







		
		
					<p>A comparative study on free-trade agreements (FTAs) involving developing or least-developed countries has been posted by the French Development Agency (AFD) and the Group for Technological Research and Exchange (GRET). The objectives of the study were ‘to feed into French thinking on the different interpretations of Article XXIV and analyse FTA examples that had not been brought as complaints to the WTO’, with the aim of identifying precedents which would allow more flexibility for ACP countries within the framework of the EPA negotiations. The study reviewed 39 agreements notified to the WTO involving developed and developing countries, and four agreements where the parties were developed countries and at least one LDC. Following this stage, 41 of these agreements were selected on the basis of the information available, and were analysed.</p><p>As regards the <b>transition period:</b></p>
<ul>

<li>four agreements had a transition period of greater than 15 years (these included the CARIFORUM-EU EPA, while for all the other interim EPAs the period was shorter, even where the degree of liberalisation varied);</li>

<li>31 agreements included an <b>asymmetric period of liberalisation</b>, including all the agreements involving the EC;</li>

<li>liberalisation was very rapid where ‘the stakes of liberalisation are low’ (moderate trade, with the level of liberalisation required either insignificant or already in place). </li>

</ul>
<p>As regards the <b>degree of liberalisation</b>, the review looks at coverage measures both in terms of the number of tariff lines liberalised and the percentage of total trade covered by the tariff liberalisation commitments (the point of contention in the IEPA negotiations). Five of the agreements had levels of liberalisation lower than 80% of tariff lines (TLs). These were the agreements between:</p>
<ul>

<li>China (35.4% of TLs and 30.3% of trade) and Pakistan (34.6% of TLs and 44.4% of trade). These correspond to the first phase of the agreement, as the second phase was still under negotiation;</li>

<li>European Free Trade Association (EFTA) (80.1% to 95.2% of TLs and 98.96% to 100% of trade) and Tunisia (77% of TLs and 71.7% of trade) ;</li>

<li>India (23.6% of TLs and 75.1% of trade) and Singapore (100%);</li>

<li>Australia (99% of trade) and Papua New Guinea (60% of trade);</li>

<li>Mexico (55.7% of TLs and 54.1 of trade) and the EU (90.3% of TLs and 98.1% of trade).</li>

</ul>
<p>In some instances this meant that the percentage of goods imported from the EU was below 60% (as per the EU-Mexico agreement).</p><p>In terms of liberalisation schedules, certain agreements allowed <b>a degree of flexibility.</b> This was the case for the EU-Tunisia agreement, which has four stages in its liberalisation process, but also for several agreements that have review clauses for a further stage of liberalisation, such as the Chile-Korea agreement, Pakistan-China, EUROMED, the European Free Trade Association (EFTA, comprising Iceland, Lichtenstein, Norway and Switzerland) or even the interim EPAs currently in force. With the exception of the Ghana-EU EPA and the CARIFORUM-EU EPA (one year and three years respectively for certain products), no agreements were found to include a moratorium, i.e. a clause that allows the party/parties ‘to postpone the start date of the liberalisation period so that the economy of the country concerned can position itself’.</p><p>As regards the <b>standstill clause</b>, ‘all the agreements refer to a basic rate of duty when implementing the liberalisation programme. This generally means the MFN duty or the specific duty applied on the date when the agreement came into effect’. The study does however raise two particular cases: the EU-South Africa TDCA, for which the basic rate of duty dates from 1996, i.e. three years before the agreement came into effect, and for which South Africa was allowed to increase duties on certain products before the old framework was dismantled; and the EU-ESA interim EPA, for which the basic rate of duty is the future COMESA CET, which for example in the case of Madagascar means a resetting of the tariff before liberalisation.</p><p>In some agreements, there was <b>special treatment given to the agricultural sector</b>, as in the US-Morocco agreement (where agricultural products are dealt with in a separate chapter and have specific safeguards), and in the Turkey-Albania and Egypt-Turkey agreements (where the two parties agree concessions on certain products, but ultimately very few agricultural products are liberalised). In the agreements involving the EFTA countries, the agricultural sector was not included, and was dealt with in specific bilateral agreements that are not notified to the WTO, and the agreements involving the Faroe Islands only covered industrial and fisheries products. In other agreements, such as the Jordan-EU or Mexico-EU Association Agreements, a review clause was included for liberalisation of the agriculture sector. According to the study, ‘this is certainly where the margins for flexibility are greatest’, as this sector is known to be sensitive for developing countries. These margins can involve a ‘minor degree of liberalisation, an extension of the transition period just for this sector, special safeguards’, specific agreements for the sector and review clauses. Sixteen of the agreements in the study were identified as containing specific safeguard measures for the agricultural sector.</p><p>In some agreements, <b>maintaining tariff quotas </b>was permitted, as in the agreements involving EFTA.</p><p>The study states that ‘all the agreements include <b>general safeguard measures </b>relating to GATT Article XIX’, and most of the agreements contain bilateral safeguard clauses. Thirty agreements contain safeguard measures that can be mobilised when there is a risk that a big rise in imports may damage the economy. These measures are applicable during the transition period for periods of one to four years, with possible extension of one to three years, whereas the WTO agreement on safeguard measures allows greater flexibility (with possible extension up to six years for developing countries). In 17 of the agreements, there are infant industry safeguard measures, notably in all the EPAs negotiated to date, but these are of limited duration (e.g. Côte d’Ivoire, 2+2 years). The study notes the presence of a ‘<b>scarcity clause</b>’ in 11 of the agreements analysed. The clause is by nature ‘not so much a safeguard [as a measure] to limit the export of these products’; it allows, in the case of the Mexico-EU agreement, for the imposition of export restrictions or taxes particularly when there is a shortage of agricultural products, and raw or essential materials. The EC-Ghana EPA also contains a clause specifying that if the agreement leads to problems of access to foodstuffs or essential commodities, Ghana can take ‘appropriate safeguard measures’.</p><p>As regards the revision clauses, the study notes that many of the agreements include revision clauses mainly for further liberalisation, but that these clauses have few restrictions and ‘do not necessarily lead to negotiations’. </p><p>The MFN clause is seldom included in the FTAs on trade in goods alone, although the EPAs between the EU and the African and Pacific countries and the FTAs among the EFTA countries are exceptions to this. In the New Zealand-Thailand agreement, the MFN clause was in fact rejected. </p><p>The FTAs in the study rarely include a section on ‘<b>development cooperation</b>’: the agreements most advanced in this respect are the EUROMED agreements, which contain provisions on ‘economic, social, cultural and financial cooperation’ and the Chile-China agreement, ‘on cooperation regarding intellectual-property, labour and environmental rights’. ‘Aid for trade’ is only mentioned in the agreements involving EFTA.</p><p>While most of the FTAs contain a provision relating to <b>national treatment</b>, which compels the countries not to favour national production over imports, the ESA-EU agreement includes an interesting clause that specifies that countries in the region may, ‘after authorisation by the EC, favour national products within the framework of fostering the development of domestic production or to support an infant industry’.</p><p>Most of the agreements include clauses that ban <b>restrictions on exports (including export taxes)</b>, however there are some exceptions to this, notably in the EPAs (unrefined sugar for Guyana, tropical woods for Suriname, and exceptions under certain conditions for Zambia, Ghana, Côte d’Ivoire, Papua New Guinea and Fiji) and in the EFTA-Chile and EFTA-Egypt agreements, where the exception covers most processed agricultural products.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
AFD-GRET, Comparative study of Free-Exchange Agreements involving developing or least-developed countries, October 2009 (French only)<br/>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id=5178&amp;doc_language=Both" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While certain agreements date from the early 1990s, it is important to emphasise that all the agreements that were studied have not to date been brought as complaints to the WTO, and this despite the significant flexibility in some of the agreements when compared to Article XXIV of GATT in respect of the degree of liberalisation of trade. Whereas some ACP requests have been taken into consideration by the EU and partially resolved (notably in the SADC negotiations), other requests have been left unaddressed.</p><p>While the study suggests that IEPAs include specific agricultural safeguard arrangements, this is not in fact the case, with agricultural safeguards being subsumed within the general safeguard arrangements. Given that the circumstances giving rise to the need for specific agricultural safeguards in ACP-EU trade relations arise from the structural nature of trade distortions linked to evolving patterns of CAP assistance to the EU food-and-agricultural sector, a strong case exists for the inclusion of food-and-agriculture-sector-specific safeguards in the IEPA agreements.</p><p>The detailed examination of these different FTAs, and in particular the degree of liberalisation in the EU-Mexico FTA (with only 54.09% liberalisation of imports from the EU), casts a new light on the EPA negotiations, and in particular the current discussions between the EU and the two regions of west Africa and central Africa, as the EU has to date declined the market access offers proposed by west and central African negotiators (of 61% and 71% respectively).</p><p>As the study points out, ‘where there are significant levels of trade between countries as well as sensitive sectors, then liberalisation is often less rapid and the agreements contain considerable potential for flexibility’. The importance of trading with the EU for west, central and southern Africa (where imports from the EU represent 32%, 45% and 33% of these regions’ total imports) could in certain cases justify a lower degree of liberalisation and specific clauses for agricultural development. </p><p>The issue of the interpretation of Article XXIV of GATT is not a new element in the EPA negotiations, but this French-commissioned study enables the issue to be considered objectively, and reopens the debate in a slightly unsettled European political context, given the uncertainties related to the new Commission and implications at the level of potential new orientations for trade negotiations. </p><p>While certain agreements date from the early 1990s, it is important to emphasise that all the agreements that were studied have not to date been brought as complaints to the WTO, and this despite the significant flexibility in some of the agreements when compared to Article XXIV of GATT in respect of the degree of liberalisation of trade. Whereas some ACP requests have been taken into consideration by the EU and partially resolved (notably in the SADC negotiations), other requests have been left unaddressed.</p><p>While the study suggests that IEPAs include specific agricultural safeguard arrangements, this is not in fact the case, with agricultural safeguards being subsumed within the general safeguard arrangements. Given that the circumstances giving rise to the need for specific agricultural safeguards in ACP-EU trade relations arise from the structural nature of trade distortions linked to evolving patterns of CAP assistance to the EU food-and-agricultural sector, a strong case exists for the inclusion of food-and-agriculture-sector-specific safeguards in the IEPA agreements.</p><p>The detailed examination of these different FTAs, and in particular the degree of liberalisation in the EU-Mexico FTA (with only 54.09% liberalisation of imports from the EU), casts a new light on the EPA negotiations, and in particular the current discussions between the EU and the two regions of west Africa and central Africa, as the EU has to date declined the market access offers proposed by west and central African negotiators (of 61% and 71% respectively).</p><p>As the study points out, ‘where there are significant levels of trade between countries as well as sensitive sectors, then liberalisation is often less rapid and the agreements contain considerable potential for flexibility’. The importance of trading with the EU for west, central and southern Africa (where imports from the EU represent 32%, 45% and 33% of these regions’ total imports) could in certain cases justify a lower degree of liberalisation and specific clauses for agricultural development. </p><p>The issue of the interpretation of Article XXIV of GATT is not a new element in the EPA negotiations, but this French-commissioned study enables the issue to be considered objectively, and reopens the debate in a slightly unsettled European political context, given the uncertainties related to the new Commission and implications at the level of potential new orientations for trade negotiations. </p>
		</div>
		

	</article>


</section>							
