																																,

							<a href="/en/Agriculture/(topics)/7812/(search)/simple">WTO</a>
							
																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																																											
							
		</div>
		
					<h1>ACP resolution on the WTO</h1>

			<h4>
			
												09 December 2009
										</h4>

				</header>







		
		
					<p>At the 90th session of the ACP Council of Ministers, a resolution was adopted on the 7th session of the Ministerial conference. The resolution expressed general concerns over the process through which the negotiations were being carried forward. Specifically with regard to agricultural issues, the resolution called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘a specific article on agricultural commodities’ in line with previous texts;</li>

<li>any agreement on modalities to take account of ‘the need for appropriate policy space’ that allows ‘ACP countries to pursue agricultural policies that are supportive of their development goals, poverty reduction strategies, food security and livelihood concerns’;</li>

<li>modalities which ensure ‘the maintenance of long-standing preferential access’ and which foster ‘improved market access for the agricultural products of ACP countries, both in primary and processed forms’;</li>

<li>modalities which adequately address all ACP concerns;</li>

<li>the resolution of issues related to ‘long-standing preferences and preference erosion … by means of trade-based solutions over an implementation period of at least ten years’ and for the adoption of the ‘necessary accompanying measures to enable the preference-dependent countries to adapt to a liberalised trading environment during and beyond the transition period’;</li>

<li>no reduction of ambition with regard to commitments on reducing domestic agricultural support programmes.</li>

</ul>
<p>Additional provisions dealing with banana, sugar and cotton issues were included in the WTO resolution (see accompanying articles on ACP resolutions on bananas, sugar and cotton issues).</p><p>The resolution also called for an ‘early harvest’ on issues affecting LDCs and the full accommodation of small and vulnerable economies.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
ACP Secretariat, Resolution of ACP Ministers, ACP/25/014/09, 19 November 2009<br/>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id=5186&amp;doc_language=Both" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id...</a></p><p>
CTA-GRET note on the key issues for ACP in the run up to the 7th WTO Ministerial meeting<br/>
<a href="http://dgroups.org/file2.axd/17f5e1c7-797c-4f44-9ee6-343316c63642/Microsoft_Word_-_EN_WTO_Geneva_Ministerial_Conference_November_2009_final.pdf" target="_self">http://dgroups.org/file2.axd/17f5e1c7-797c-4f44-9ee6-343316c63642/Micros...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The resolution represents the consensus position in the ACP on these issues and constitutes the assertion of ACP concerns on these agricultural issues in the run-up to the 7th WTO Ministerial conference. It provides an effective benchmark against which to judge the outcome of the forthcoming Ministerial meeting. However, it should be noted that WTO Director-General Lamy has stressed that the forthcoming meeting is not essentially about the Doha Round negotiations, but more about the day-to-day functioning of the WTO as an institution regulating international trade relations. This would suggest that there are unlikely to be any major breakthroughs on issues of concern to the ACP at the forthcoming Ministerial meeting.</p>
		</div>
		

	</article>


</section>							
